#Text=2012 Report on Gender Equality and Development says US women have room for progress
#Text=Friday , September 27 , 2013
#Text=Tuesday , World Bank released the 2012 World Development Report on Gender Equality and Development .
#Text=The United States is referred to many times , often as a benchmark to foster understanding of recent gains for women in other parts of the globe .
#Text=At the same time , United States women still lag behind US men in a number of areas .
#Text=In 2012 , the authors note women in the United States still face challenges economically and socially .
#Text=They are represented disproportionately in certain professions like teaching and nursing .
#Text=They are paid less than their male counterparts .
#Text=Jobs traditionally held by women also result in lower wages for men who hold these jobs .
#Text=They are under-represented at the highest level of business , with only 28 of Fortune 1000 companies having a female chief executive officer .
#Text=The bottom 20 % of women economically have a slightly higher birth rate than their peers in the top 20 % .

#Text=Immigrants to the United States from Southeast Asia and India have higher than expected male to female birth ratios , which the report authors suggest is partially deliberate sex selection based on cultural attitudes from home countries .
#Text=In 2009 , over half a million US women were victims of intimate partner violence .
#Text=The report suggests US men have greater pension assets than US women .
#Text=When compared to elderly US men , elderly women in the United States are more likely to live alone than with a spouse .
#Text=US women are disproportionately under-represented in local police forces , accounting for less than 20 % of all police officers .
#Text=Women in the United States also bear a higher percentage of housework duties than men at 61 % .
#Text=When US women take part time work while raising children , they find it difficult to use that work experience to gain future full time employment .
#Text=US women are disincentivized from re-entering the workforce after giving birth because of the high cost of childcare .
#Text=A suffrage parade in the United States in 1912 Image : National Archives and Records Administration .
#Text=Many of the gains for United States women took place a while ago and took a long time to get .
#Text=It took 40 years , 1870 – 1910 , to see major improvements in the percentage of girls aged 6 to 12 attending school .
#Text=In 1921 , after women got the right to vote in the United States , the United States Congress passed the Promotion of the Welfare and Hygiene of Maternity and Infancy Act .
#Text=This assisted in lowering infant mortality from 23 % to 15 % .
#Text=Affirmative Action Demonstration in 2003 in the District of Colombia Image : Joseluis89 .

#Text=The report says affirmative action in the United States resulted in jobs transferring from men to women , but the authors hedged and did not draw a conclusion about the economic impact of these legislative efforts other than to say the impact was not negative .
#Text=Many of the legislative victories for United States women came early compared to developing countries .
#Text=Property rights for women , while later than some of their European counterparts like Norway and the United Kingdom , started to come by 1848 .
#Text=That year , the Married Women ’s Property Act was passed in New York .
#Text=It was the first legislation of its kind in the country .
#Text=Other states soon followed .
#Text=Women got suffrage on a state-by-state level in the country until they got federal suffrage in 1920 .
#Text=Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 barred discrimination against women and allowed married women to make loans without their husband 's consent .
#Text=In 1980 , airlines were barred from discriminating against flight attendances for their marital status during the hiring and firing stage .

#Text=The number of United States respondents agreeing with the proposition " a university education is more important for a boy than for a girl " decreased from about 14 % in the period between 1994 and 1999 to about about 9 % in the period between 2005 and 2007 .
#Text=Similarly , the number of people who agreed with " when jobs are scarce , men should have more right to a job than women " decreased from 19 % to about 8 % over the same period .
#Text=The report cites current research from the United States and England showing the more education a mother has , the better the outcomes for her children will be .
#Text=Average national scores on the 2009 Programme for International Student Assessment maths test Image : StatSilk .
#Text=Currently in the United States , females academically outperform their male counterparts in all academic areas including [ [ mathematics|math ] and science .
#Text=On the Programme for International Student Assessment math test though , US boys tested better than US girls by a score of roughly 495 to 480 .
#Text=US girls outperform boys on the literacy test with mean scores of approximately 510 to 490 .
#Text=In this regard , the report suggests US girls ' performance patterns resemble global ones .
#Text=Mali 's percentage of girls in primary school is equivalent to the United States in 1810 at around 34 % .
#Text=Burkino Faso is worse , matching the United States in 1780 with a percentage of roughly 25 % .
#Text=Niger 's current enrollment for girls is around 50 % , around the same percentage as the United States in 1900 .
